[2]
Date: Sat, 25 Jun 2005
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: People's Daily Online, 24 Jun 2005 [edited]
<http://english.people.com.cn/200506/24/eng20050624_192146.html>


Waterfowl in Vietnam's central province infected with bird flu
--------------------------------------------------------------
1/5 of total waterfowl flocks in Vietnam's central Quang Tri province have
just been found to contract bird flu virus strain H5N1, local newspaper
Saigon Liberation reported on Friday [24 Jun 2005].

The provincial Veterinarian Bureau has culled over 23 000 waterfowl, mainly
ducks, in the 38 infected flocks. It will further the culling if the 144
untested flocks prove to be infected with H5N1.

Vietnam, which has seen no bird flu outbreaks since April 2005, culled a
flock of 6700 chickens in southern Ben Tre province in mid-June after
specimens from 6000 dead or sick poultry in the flock tested positive to H5N1.

An international team, consisting of top virologists and epidemiologists
from Chinese Hong Kong, Japan, the United Kingdom, and the United States,
arrived in Vietnam on 6 Jun 2005 to study the possibility of more
widespread H5N1 human transmission, changes in the virus strain, and the
likelihood of increased person-to-person transmission, said a press release
by the office of the World Health Organization (WHO) Representative in
Vietnam on Friday.

"What has happened in Vietnam may have public health implications for the
entire world, and will be crucial in preparing for a possible pandemic,"
Hans Troedsson, WHO Representative in the country, was quoted in the release.

In mid-June, the Preventive Medicine Department under Vietnam's Health
Ministry announced that 4 local people were infected with H5N1 from 1-17
June, including 2 from Hanoi capital city, 1 from northern Hai Duong
province, and 1 from central Nghe An province.

The newly confirmed cases bring the total in Vietnam since mid- December
2004 to 59 cases, of which 18 were fatal. Since the 1st bird flu patient
was detected in Vietnam in late 2003, Vietnam had detected 86 human cases
of bird flu infection, including 38 fatalities, in 31 cities and provinces,
the department confirmed late last week.

